description:
In feed.rs, link URLs from feed entries are sanitized with ammonia::clean() and then interpolated directly into HTML attribute context:

  let safe_url = ammonia::clean(url);
  html.push_str(&format!(r#"<p><a href="{safe_url}">{safe_url}</a></p>"#));

ammonia::clean() strips HTML tags but does not HTML-encode bare text. A URL containing & in its query string (e.g., https://example.com/page?a=1&b=2) passes through unchanged. The resulting HTML attribute href="https://example.com/page?a=1&b=2" is invalid HTML — the & should be &amp;. Strict HTML parsers (including some ActivityPub clients) will misparse the URL, breaking the link.

The same issue appears in the truncation suffix:
  html.push_str(&format!(r#"… <a href="{safe_url}">read more</a>"#));

Fix: use a proper URL-to-HTML-attribute encoder (e.g., encode & as &amp;, " as &quot;) or build the anchor through ammonia by sanitizing a pre-formed <a> tag rather than interpolating into a format string.
